If $(X, d_X)$ and $(Y, d_Y)$ are metric spaces, $f : X \rightarrow Y$ is a function, and $x_0 \in X$, then $f$ is <i>continuous at $x_0$</i> if and only if, for every $\varepsilon > 0$, there is a $\delta > 0$ such that $d_Y(f(x), f(x_0)) < \varepsilon$ whenever $d_X(x, x_0) < \delta$.<br /><br />


